structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with embedded diagrams and downloadable PDF files
subsector: Commercial and Institutional Buildings and Facilities
structured_data.data_format: Web page with embedded tables, diagrams, and downloadable PDFs
structured_data.description: Dataset from Umweltbundesamt (German Federal Environment Agency) covering heat consumption and production for fossil and renewable energy sources in Germany. The dataset presents heat consumption across sectors (private households, industry, commercial/trade/services), application areas (space heating, process heat, hot water, cooling), and energy carriers. Data spans from 2008 to 2023, with analysis of energy efficiency measures and the increasing role of renewable energies in heat provision. Heat accounts for over 50% of total final energy consumption in Germany. The dataset includes information on district heating generation and energy carrier distribution.

structured_data.description: German Federal Statistical Office (Destatis) thematic portal section on energy usage. Part of the 'Branchen und Unternehmen' (Sectors and Enterprises) category, this section provides statistical information on energy consumption and usage patterns in Germany. The portal serves as a gateway to various energy-related datasets and statistics maintained by Destatis.

structured_data.name: Endenergieverbrauch der privaten Haushalte pro Person 1995 – 2021 nach Bundesländern
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface query on Statistikportal.de; data accessible through the UGRdL (Umweltökonomische Gesamtrechnungen der Länder) results portal
structured_data.data_format: HTML table embedded in web interface
structured_data.description: Final energy consumption (Endenergieverbrauch) of private households per capita from 1995 to 2021, broken down by German federal states (Bundesländer). Data measured in Gigajoule per person. Provider: Länderarbeitskreis Energiebilanzen (State Working Group on Energy Balances), with model results from the Arbeitskreis Umweltökonomische Gesamtrechnungen der Länder (Working Group on Environmental-Economic Accounts of the States) and the Arbeitsgemeinschaft Energiebilanzen (Working Group on Energy Balances) for Germany. Data last updated September 2022.
structured_data.granularity: Regional (by German federal states/Bundesländer) and national (Deutschland)

structured_data.name: EDGAR v8.0 - Global Greenhouse Gas Emissions
structured_data.method_of_access: Downloadable files (ZIP format) available through direct download links from the EDGAR dataset portal
structured_data.data_format: Excel (.xlsx), ZIP archives containing overview tables
structured_data.description: EDGAR v8.0 is a global greenhouse gas emissions database developed by the Joint Research Centre (JRC) in collaboration with the International Energy Agency (IEA). It provides estimates for three main greenhouse gases (CO2, CH4, N2O) and fluorinated gases per sector and country. The dataset covers time series from 1970-2022, with monthly data also available. CO2 emissions are provided separately for fossil and biogenic components. Data incorporates IEA energy statistics, FAO agricultural data, and USGS/UNFCCC reporting. Updated spatial proxies for power generation, industrial facilities, and livestock distribution were implemented using Gridded Livestock of the World 2015 (GLW4) maps. The database is maintained by the European Commission's Joint Research Centre.
structured_data.granularity: Country-level (includes Germany as part of global coverage)

structured_data.name: Energiebedingte Emissionen von Klimagasen und Luftschadstoffen
structured_data.method_of_access: Web interface with embedded visualizations and downloadable PDF charts
structured_data.data_format: Web page with embedded charts, PDF diagrams
structured_data.description: Dataset from Umweltbundesamt (German Federal Environment Agency) covering energy-related greenhouse gas and air pollutant emissions in Germany. The dataset shows that energy-related emissions accounted for approximately 85% of German greenhouse gas emissions in 2022. Primary data sources include public electricity and heat generation in power plants, refineries, transportation sector (23.3% in 2021), industry (18%), private households (13%), and commercial/service sectors (4%). The dataset tracks emissions trends from 1990 to 2022, showing a general declining trend with temporary disruptions during economic crises (2009) and the COVID-19 pandemic (2020). Emissions consist primarily of CO2 (98%), with smaller contributions from methane and nitrous oxide. The data includes information on CO2 emissions from electricity generation, greenhouse gas emissions from the German electricity mix, and declining classical air pollutants.

decision_log.summary: Reviewed 6 documents from German and European sources. This batch contains highly promising material for stationary_energy sector GHGI data extraction. Multiple documents are from authoritative German government sources (UBA, Destatis, Statistikportal) and EU institutions (EDGAR), with clear evidence of structured energy data, emissions figures, sectoral breakdowns, and time series. The UBA documents are particularly rich with detailed energy consumption and emissions data by sector and fuel type. Regional statistics and EU-level datasets also present.
decision_log.reasoning: Identified five highly relevant documents with strong indicators of structured GHGI data. The UBA (Umweltbundesamt) pages contain detailed sectoral breakdowns of energy consumption and emissions with specific percentages, time series data (1990-2023), and references to underlying datasets. Destatis and Statistikportal offer official German statistical energy data with tables and regional breakdowns. EDGAR provides EU-level harmonized GHG emissions data by sector and country. These sources are authoritative, government-backed, and explicitly contain or link to the type of structured data needed for stationary_energy sector analysis. The BDEW and Statistik-Nord documents were excluded as they appear to be portal pages or regional-only data without direct access to comprehensive national stationary energy data.

decision_log.summary: Excellent collection of authoritative German government sources for residential building energy consumption and emissions. The extracted data includes primary official sources (Umweltbundesamt, Destatis, Statistikportal) with national and regional granularity covering 1990-2023. All sources are credible government agencies. Data directly addresses the search plan objectives for household fuel combustion, energy consumption, and GHG emissions inventory. EDGAR v8.0 provides international validation. The main limitation is that extracted descriptions indicate data availability but actual detailed tables/values for specific emission categories (natural gas, LPG, firewood combustion) require deeper access to underlying datasets.
decision_log.reasoning: Strong recommendation for DEEP_DIVE rather than immediate ACCEPT because: (1) All sources are confirmed credible and relevant, indicating high probability of finding required data; (2) The extracted descriptions confirm data availability but actual quantitative tables need to be accessed and reviewed; (3) Specific household fuel combustion data (natural gas, LPG, firewood) are mentioned as available but not yet extracted; (4) UBA and Destatis websites likely contain downloadable datasets (PDFs, Excel files) that need to be examined for specific emission categories and activity data; (5) One additional targeted search could efficiently extract the actual data tables needed for GHGI compilation. This is a 'max 1-2 attempts' scenario where high-confidence sources need minimal additional investigation.

decision_log.summary: The extracted structured data represents a strong collection of official German government sources for residential building energy consumption and emissions inventory. Five datasets have been identified from highly credible institutions: Umweltbundesamt (UBA), Destatis (German Federal Statistical Office), Statistikportal.de, EDGAR v8.0, and regional energy balance working groups. The data covers the stationary energy sector with specific focus on residential buildings, commercial facilities, and energy industries. Time series data spans from 1990-2023, providing comprehensive historical context. All sources are government-affiliated or internationally recognized (JRC/EC). The datasets address the core GHGI requirements for Germany's residential and commercial building energy consumption and associated greenhouse gas emissions.
decision_log.reasoning: The extracted structured data meets all ACCEPT criteria: (1) Official national GHGI activity data for Germany is available from multiple credible government sources; (2) German Federal Statistical Office (Destatis) and UBA data provide authoritative government statistics for the target sector; (3) Key emission categories for stationary energy/buildings are covered (residential buildings, commercial facilities, energy industries, with specific data on fuel combustion, heating, and electricity use); (4) Strong indication that these websites contain the desired data - UBA and Destatis are primary sources for German GHGI reporting and are referenced in official inventory submissions. The data quality, source credibility, temporal coverage (1990-2023), and sectoral granularity are all appropriate for GHGI purposes. No gaps identified that would prevent use of this data for Germany's residential building energy consumption and emissions inventory. This represents a successful search outcome with actionable, high-quality data sources.
